WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.162 --> 00:00:04.620
MALE SPEAKER: Please join me
in a massive round of applause

00:00:04.620 --> 00:00:05.660
to welcome Ben Miller.

00:00:05.660 --> 00:00:08.921
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:12.702
Hello.

00:00:12.702 --> 00:00:13.827
BEN MILLER: Thank you, Rob.

00:00:13.827 --> 00:00:15.280
Thank you all so
much for coming.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.020
I really appreciate that
spontaneous welcome.

00:00:18.020 --> 00:00:19.472
Thank you.

00:00:19.472 --> 00:00:21.180
MALE SPEAKER: Ben,
you've written a book.

00:00:21.180 --> 00:00:21.640
BEN MILLER: I have.

00:00:21.640 --> 00:00:22.120
MALE SPEAKER: It's very good.

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:23.850
I finished it last night.

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:26.394
It's about the search for
extraterrestrial life--

00:00:26.394 --> 00:00:27.060
BEN MILLER: Yes.

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:28.360
MALE SPEAKER: --what
that might look like--

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:28.890
BEN MILLER: Yes.

00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:31.098
MALE SPEAKER: --and how we
might go about finding it.

00:00:31.098 --> 00:00:32.960
BEN MILLER: Exactly.

00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:34.770
MALE SPEAKER: Why did
you write the book?

00:00:34.770 --> 00:00:36.610
BEN MILLER: I think it was a
bit of a midlife crisis thing,

00:00:36.610 --> 00:00:37.110
really.

00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:41.990
I mean, I just got very
into-- my scientific training

00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:44.250
was in physics.

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:46.160
I've just always loved science.

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:48.210
It's not something
I've done as a career,

00:00:48.210 --> 00:00:49.360
it's always been a hobby.

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:52.500
It's just something I just
really get a lot of enjoyment

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:54.630
from and a lot of pleasure from.

00:00:54.630 --> 00:00:57.450
And this book started
with a previous book.

00:00:57.450 --> 00:00:59.700
I wrote a book called "It's
Not Rocket Science," which

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:03.300
is basically-- I felt there
weren't any books out there

00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:08.450
which described the best
bits of science for people

00:01:08.450 --> 00:01:12.450
without-- for bright people
without-- a scientific training

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:13.050
or background.

00:01:13.050 --> 00:01:16.710
So I thought, well, would
it be possible to write

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:19.180
about all the bits of
science that I love

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:22.710
and explain it in
a way that, say,

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:26.080
a creative person with a
really good arts degree

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:30.110
could maybe pick up and
really get access to science.

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:30.930
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:01:30.930 --> 00:01:33.350
And this is digging deep
into that particular topic

00:01:33.350 --> 00:01:34.782
of astrobiology and [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:34.782 --> 00:01:35.490
BEN MILLER: Yeah.

00:01:35.490 --> 00:01:40.240
So when I was doing that
book, I came across-- partly,

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:43.170
I wanted to do some
stuff about DNA

00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:47.040
and the latest
advances in biology.

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:49.760
And that just got me
really interested in life,

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:52.420
you know, the physics
of life, what is life.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:56.220
I came across a brilliant
book by Erwin Schrodinger

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:01.580
called "What is Life,"
which talked, really, about,

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:06.940
how does life fit in with the
second law of thermodynamics.

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:09.249
One of the topics I hadn't
covered in the first book

00:02:09.249 --> 00:02:11.290
was entropy and the second
law of thermodynamics.

00:02:11.290 --> 00:02:13.498
So I thought, wow, is that
something that I could try

00:02:13.498 --> 00:02:17.820
and-- is that something I
could try and do justice to.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:20.880
Also, I just think
aliens is a funny topic.

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:24.960
There's something
naturally amusing about it,

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:27.600
sometimes intentionally,
sometimes unintentionally.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.094
And at the beginning of the
book, whereas, the first book,

00:02:31.094 --> 00:02:32.510
I was really in
my comfort zone, I

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:34.975
was writing about things that
I knew quite well, this book,

00:02:34.975 --> 00:02:37.100
I didn't know any of this
stuff when I started out.

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:44.020
So it was also like-- for me--
it was like my dream adult

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:45.500
education course, really.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:47.690
So I went to meet all
these amazing people,

00:02:47.690 --> 00:02:49.460
incredible people.

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:55.010
And to begin with, I had a real
embarrassment about asking them

00:02:55.010 --> 00:02:57.580
about-- one of the first
people I went to meet

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:04.330
was the head of the UNOOSA,
the UN Office of Outer Space

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:04.999
Affairs.

00:03:04.999 --> 00:03:07.290
MALE SPEAKER: She's our
ambassador if aliens come down.

00:03:07.290 --> 00:03:08.331
BEN MILLER: That's right.

00:03:08.331 --> 00:03:11.754
So the idea-- and this
was sort of where,

00:03:11.754 --> 00:03:13.170
partly, the idea
for the book came

00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:17.770
from-- the idea is that
if aliens were to land,

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:20.770
the UN needs to have a response.

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:25.330
I mean, this is literally like
if they landed in a space ship

00:03:25.330 --> 00:03:29.040
and came out and held
a press conference.

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:32.940
There would have to be
somebody-- there's somebody

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:37.007
whose job it is, at the UN,
to liaise with the aliens.

00:03:37.007 --> 00:03:38.590
MALE SPEAKER: That's
not her only job.

00:03:38.590 --> 00:03:42.030
BEN MILLER: That's
not her only job.

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:44.950
She's also got to find ghosts.

00:03:44.950 --> 00:03:47.260
No, it's not her only job.

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:52.386
That office, they basically keep
track of all the satellites.

00:03:52.386 --> 00:03:54.260
Basically, if you want
to put a satellite up,

00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:56.210
you have to talk
to UNOOSA first.

00:03:56.210 --> 00:03:59.810
And yeah, so I went to
meet her and I felt so--

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:02.185
and the story is in the
book-- I felt so embarrassed.

00:04:02.185 --> 00:04:08.940
I was going to this very eminent
Malaysian physicist who'd

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:11.759
set up the Malaysian
space program

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:13.675
and had launched the
first Malaysian satellite

00:04:13.675 --> 00:04:14.966
and was now the head of UNOOSA.

00:04:14.966 --> 00:04:17.100
And I went to have this thing.

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:19.000
And I said, well,
so could we just

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:20.870
talk about this aliens thing?

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:25.000
And I said, is it true
that if aliens land,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.990
then you're the
designated spokesman

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:30.530
on behalf of the human race?

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:35.540
And she said, yeah, it's
pretty cool, isn't it?

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:39.440
And I just had the most
brilliant chat with her

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:40.360
where we got on.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:43.970
Quickly, you start
talking about life.

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:50.773
You very quickly get on to
what makes life so special.

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:58.140
We very quickly got onto
even spiritual subjects.

00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:01.930
You know, what does it all mean.

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:02.990
What are we here for?

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:06.470
And why do we want
to talk to aliens?

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:10.270
And I began to
realize that there

00:05:10.270 --> 00:05:13.640
was real science, that you
could go-- what you could do

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:19.530
is you could take all the
latest stuff that we had found

00:05:19.530 --> 00:05:23.260
in astronomy, and you could
take all of the latest stuff

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:26.010
that we had found in
evolutionary biology,

00:05:26.010 --> 00:05:27.750
and you could put
it all together,

00:05:27.750 --> 00:05:31.170
and you could do a pretty good
job, really, of finding out

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:36.000
what life on Earth could tell
you about any other life that

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:36.870
might be out there.

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:44.100
And that's in every respect--
how it might get its start,

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:48.140
what life is in physical
terms-- you know,

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:53.350
is there any-- it's
a huge subject.

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:56.590
How would you communicate with
it if you could communicate?

00:05:56.590 --> 00:06:00.650
Just say, for
example, we did manage

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:02.390
to receive some kind of signal.

00:06:02.390 --> 00:06:03.860
How would we know
it was a signal?

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:07.960
Could we decode it?

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:11.610
If we couldn't decode
it, what information

00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:14.070
could we get from it?

00:06:14.070 --> 00:06:16.097
And it becomes a
really-- It's just--

00:06:16.097 --> 00:06:17.680
MALE SPEAKER: I
think, on that topic--

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:17.980
BEN MILLER: --a
fabulous subject.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:19.680
MALE SPEAKER: --there was a
point where you were talking

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:21.820
about Zipf's law and dolphins--
and we'll move on to the that--

00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:22.110
BEN MILLER: Ah.

00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:22.860
MALE SPEAKER: --which is weird.

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:23.360
BEN MILLER: Oh my god.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:24.818
MALE SPEAKER: But
essentially, even

00:06:24.818 --> 00:06:27.620
if you can't understand
what is in a signal,

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:31.279
you could prove that it
had intelligence behind it.

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:33.820
BEN MILLER: Well, yes, I imagine
that information theory will

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:35.653
be bread and butter to
a lot of people here,

00:06:35.653 --> 00:06:37.250
but it was very new to me.

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:42.110
And the idea that you
could-- basically,

00:06:42.110 --> 00:06:45.380
the mathematical
properties of language

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:48.010
are there whether or
not you can understand

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:50.120
what the message says or not.

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:54.790
So you could know
that something--

00:06:54.790 --> 00:06:56.450
you can't know that
it is language,

00:06:56.450 --> 00:06:58.010
that it is
communication, but you

00:06:58.010 --> 00:07:02.170
can see whether it has the
properties of language.

00:07:02.170 --> 00:07:04.980
And you can see how
complex a language

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:08.549
it could possibly
be without knowing

00:07:08.549 --> 00:07:09.590
the content, the message.

00:07:09.590 --> 00:07:11.090
MALE SPEAKER: If you analyze
the speech patterns of a child,

00:07:11.090 --> 00:07:12.290
they're less complicated
than the speech

00:07:12.290 --> 00:07:12.900
patterns of an adult.

00:07:12.900 --> 00:07:13.200
BEN MILLER: Exactly.

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:14.574
So they did this
brilliant thing.

00:07:14.574 --> 00:07:20.679
So one of the stories in
the book is about how--

00:07:20.679 --> 00:07:21.970
and this was really news to me.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:25.652
I hadn't realized that we think
of ourselves as very special.

00:07:25.652 --> 00:07:27.110
Homo sapiens, we
think of ourselves

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:28.810
as being really extraordinary.

00:07:28.810 --> 00:07:30.930
We are intelligent.

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:38.460
It began with the domestication
of animals and farming.

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:40.370
And then we built civilizations.

00:07:40.370 --> 00:07:41.920
And then we discovered language.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:45.580
And we have this story
that we tell ourselves

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:49.262
where we are completely
unique on the planet.

00:07:49.262 --> 00:07:50.720
And it's really,
really interesting

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:54.670
to discover that all
those traits are there

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:55.740
in other species.

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:58.240
MALE SPEAKER: You talk about
farming as something ants do.

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:00.634
BEN MILLER: Ants, yeah.

00:08:00.634 --> 00:08:03.760
There's a South
American ant that's

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:08.942
been farming, fungus farming,
for about 6 million years.

00:08:08.942 --> 00:08:11.150
MALE SPEAKER: They treat
the fungus with antibiotics.

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:13.274
BEN MILLER: They treat the
fungus with antibiotics,

00:08:13.274 --> 00:08:15.660
they farm it, they cultivate
it, they use it as food.

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:17.170
It's farming.

00:08:17.170 --> 00:08:18.400
You can't argue with it.

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:19.800
It's definitely farming.

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:27.860
The crow family-- I met
this fabulous professor

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:30.360
at the University of Cambridge
who's done a lot of work with

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:34.970
crows and has shown that
crows have cognitive abilities

00:08:34.970 --> 00:08:39.350
not just on a par with
chimpanzees, but in some cases,

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:43.770
better than chimpanzees.

00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:48.880
And you start to form
this picture of-- it

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:50.570
starts to become very,
very interesting.

00:08:50.570 --> 00:08:55.960
And you see our own
very lucky position

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:57.740
as being more of an
accident, really,

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:04.380
than a vital last step in a long
chain of progressive evolution.

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:05.739
It's really interesting.

00:09:05.739 --> 00:09:07.780
MALE SPEAKER: And you call
out the intelligence--

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:11.520
so, the example of convergence,
where different elements come

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:13.910
about through entirely
different evolutionary paths--

00:09:13.910 --> 00:09:14.860
BEN MILLER: That's
a great example.

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:16.120
MALE SPEAKER: --and
intelligence being one of those.

00:09:16.120 --> 00:09:16.953
BEN MILLER: Exactly.

00:09:16.953 --> 00:09:20.330
So again, new to me was this
idea of convergent evolution.

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:23.500
We've all heard of
divergent evolution.

00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:26.400
Organisms speciate over
time, and we end up

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.900
with a planet that's full of
all kinds of different things.

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:33.220
But there's also
convergent evolution.

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:39.810
So things like wings have
evolved independently,

00:09:39.810 --> 00:09:42.050
maybe half a dozen times,
in different species,

00:09:42.050 --> 00:09:44.170
completely unrelated.

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:48.510
In fact, convergence is such
a problem for biologists

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:50.940
that many mistakes
have been made

00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:56.252
since the 19th century,
where one creature from one

00:09:56.252 --> 00:09:58.793
part of the planet looks so like
a creature from another part

00:09:58.793 --> 00:10:00.584
of the planet, they
believe they're related

00:10:00.584 --> 00:10:03.690
and only later find out that
they are on a completely

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:05.470
different evolutionary path.

00:10:05.470 --> 00:10:07.219
MALE SPEAKER: I was
reading, this morning,

00:10:07.219 --> 00:10:09.890
that carnivorous plants have
evolved nine times in five

00:10:09.890 --> 00:10:11.390
different orders.

00:10:11.390 --> 00:10:12.200
It's [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:13.658
BEN MILLER: And
this is everywhere.

00:10:13.658 --> 00:10:18.720
So teeth, eyes-- our eyes are
remarkably similar, in design,

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:20.310
to octopus eyes, for example.

00:10:20.310 --> 00:10:25.580
But obviously, the common
ancestor of us and the octopus

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:32.010
is-- you're going right back
to the Cambrian explosion

00:10:32.010 --> 00:10:35.780
540 million years ago.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:37.600
It's really striking.

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:41.180
And intelligence--
there is intelligence

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:47.880
in-- arguably, intelligence in--
dolphins, in crows, in octopus.

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:50.290
You could include dogs, cats.

00:10:50.290 --> 00:10:53.289
There's all kinds of
different creatures.

00:10:53.289 --> 00:10:54.830
Of all of those,
the most interesting

00:10:54.830 --> 00:10:57.570
is probably octopuses
and mammals,

00:10:57.570 --> 00:11:00.550
because again, it's
such a long way back.

00:11:00.550 --> 00:11:03.080
But even with crows,
for a common ancestor

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:06.650
between crows and us,
you've got to go back

00:11:06.650 --> 00:11:13.920
to what they call an amniote,
something that was basically

00:11:13.920 --> 00:11:15.430
just laying eggs on land.

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:16.450
MALE SPEAKER: Well, let's
go right back [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:16.450 --> 00:11:18.590
So you open the book
with extremophiles--

00:11:18.590 --> 00:11:21.020
so, bacteria in a rock here?

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:21.929
How do I--

00:11:21.929 --> 00:11:23.470
BEN MILLER: There's
been three-- what

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:29.680
was happening is all-- three
different areas of science

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:32.999
are all converging on
the same point, really.

00:11:32.999 --> 00:11:34.540
We've had the Kepler
Space Telescope,

00:11:34.540 --> 00:11:39.455
which has shown us that
Earth-like planets are common.

00:11:39.455 --> 00:11:40.830
So whereas 20
years ago, we might

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:42.160
have believed there
were no other planets

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:44.040
outside the solar
system, we now know

00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:45.900
Earth-like planets are common.

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:51.080
And maybe something like
one in 1,000 solar systems

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:54.930
is like our own, with
a big, cold Jupiter,

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:59.220
terrestrial planets the right
distance from a Sun-like star

00:11:59.220 --> 00:12:02.380
to have water on their surface.

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:04.330
We know that these
things are common.

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:05.540
So that was one area.

00:12:05.540 --> 00:12:08.880
There's another area, which was
extremophiles, which has also

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:11.680
been going in parallel, where
we've discovered that life

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:18.620
on Earth is much more resilient,
creative, resourceful than we

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:20.160
ever realized.

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:23.050
We thought that there was a
certain zone of temperatures,

00:12:23.050 --> 00:12:28.459
acidities, pressures, radiation
levels where life could exist.

00:12:28.459 --> 00:12:30.750
And time and time again,
we've discovered that's wrong.

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:34.530
You always find some bacterium
somewhere, very, very happy

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.440
to live in those conditions.

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:40.730
And then finally, there's
been the advances-- again,

00:12:40.730 --> 00:12:42.700
this is all new to me,
and it's really, really

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:45.670
great stuff-- advances
in evolutionary biology.

00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:47.820
So we've now got some
really good theories that

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:53.690
make an awful lot of
sense, not the Darwin warm

00:12:53.690 --> 00:12:58.880
pond that you may heard
of, but this idea that life

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:02.140
began in alkaline
hydrothermal vents.

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:05.930
Because you get a particularly
unique situation there where

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:07.710
you've got lots of
transition metals.

00:13:07.710 --> 00:13:09.970
One thing we do know is
that life, as we know it,

00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:11.325
adores transition metals.

00:13:11.325 --> 00:13:14.830
It kind of uses transition
metals as little batteries

00:13:14.830 --> 00:13:19.870
to borrow electrons from
and pay electrons back

00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:21.990
when it suits it.

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:25.520
You have this great-- it's
an electrochemical cell,

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:32.210
basically, because the first
sea waters were acidic.

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:34.890
And if you have an
alkaline hydrothermal vent,

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:38.180
you essentially get,
across the membrane,

00:13:38.180 --> 00:13:43.790
the semi-permeable membrane of
the bubbles inside the vent,

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:46.640
these gel-like iron
sulfide bubbles,

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:49.220
you get this charge separation.

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:53.970
And that can be used to
drive-- as an energy source,

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:58.380
to drive-- the formation
of long-chain molecules.

00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:04.590
So suddenly, so many
missing steps of the jigsaw

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:07.760
are almost falling into place.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:11.340
And you begin to have an
explanation for the beginning

00:14:11.340 --> 00:14:15.320
of life that sort of makes
sense in physical, biological,

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:16.839
and chemical terms.

00:14:16.839 --> 00:14:18.380
MALE SPEAKER: So
once you have that--

00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:19.340
BEN MILLER: You've
got these three areas

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:20.173
all coming together.

00:14:20.173 --> 00:14:23.250
And now everyone's going,
shit, there's life everywhere.

00:14:23.250 --> 00:14:27.630
Because we think volcanic
Earth-like planets

00:14:27.630 --> 00:14:29.810
would be common.

00:14:29.810 --> 00:14:32.450
We know that life on Earth
started, pretty much,

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:34.530
out of the box.

00:14:34.530 --> 00:14:38.170
The early Earth, as you know,
was pummeled with asteroids.

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:41.450
We're now pretty sure
that life started even

00:14:41.450 --> 00:14:43.744
during that period.

00:14:43.744 --> 00:14:46.160
So that means that it couldn't
really have been in a pond.

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:48.160
A pond doesn't make sense
if the Earth's getting

00:14:48.160 --> 00:14:49.159
pummeled with asteroids.

00:14:49.159 --> 00:14:53.230
But a hydrothermal vent
on the ocean floor,

00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:55.620
that makes complete sense.

00:14:55.620 --> 00:14:58.190
And we know that these
planets are common.

00:14:58.190 --> 00:15:00.380
And we know that life
can exist in such

00:15:00.380 --> 00:15:04.060
an extraordinary wide
variety of conditions.

00:15:04.060 --> 00:15:07.520
In fact, we're
the extremophiles.

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:10.850
This is the thing that
we've basically figured out,

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:19.560
that microbial life didn't-- the
first microbial life basically

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:24.190
used metals as a food source.

00:15:24.190 --> 00:15:27.330
Now all life, the
life that produces

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:29.270
the food, the sugars
that we like to eat,

00:15:29.270 --> 00:15:33.030
rips electrons off water,
stuffs them onto carbon dioxide

00:15:33.030 --> 00:15:34.700
to make long-chain molecules.

00:15:34.700 --> 00:15:38.230
Well, the first life
ripped electrons just

00:15:38.230 --> 00:15:41.680
from metals that were
in the vent, again,

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:44.340
stuffed them onto carbon dioxide
to make long-chain molecules.

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:46.756
MALE SPEAKER: So once you have
that early microbial life--

00:15:46.756 --> 00:15:49.133
which, let's assume that it's
quite abundant throughout

00:15:49.133 --> 00:15:50.080
the universe--

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:52.020
BEN MILLER: Yeah, this
is the difficult bit.

00:15:52.020 --> 00:15:53.480
Yeah, this is the
tricky bit, isn't it?

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:55.355
MALE SPEAKER: How do
you get to complex life?

00:15:55.355 --> 00:15:58.700
BEN MILLER: So yeah,
microbial life-- common.

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:01.322
Most reasonable people,
I think-- certainly,

00:16:01.322 --> 00:16:02.242
once you've read--

00:16:02.242 --> 00:16:03.950
MALE SPEAKER: I'm
pretty convinced, yeah.

00:16:03.950 --> 00:16:07.880
BEN MILLER: --this book--
you would believe, as I say,

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:09.670
it works straight
out of the box.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:12.560
The trick is to get to
complex, multicellular life.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:16.400
Now multicellularity,
cells just getting together

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:20.440
to make life easier for
themselves, that has, again,

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:23.260
emerged many, many times
throughout history of life

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:23.760
on Earth.

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:28.035
And you get multicellularity
within a billion,

00:16:28.035 --> 00:16:31.650
a billion and a half years
of the first sign of life

00:16:31.650 --> 00:16:32.510
on Earth.

00:16:32.510 --> 00:16:35.300
Complex multicellularity,
where you get organisms

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:41.540
with tissues-- and animals
would be the best example

00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:48.230
of that-- that has emerged,
maybe, a handful of times.

00:16:48.230 --> 00:16:49.855
MALE SPEAKER: But
still more than once.

00:16:49.855 --> 00:16:52.120
BEN MILLER: There's
three types of algae,

00:16:52.120 --> 00:16:55.590
there's basically fungi,
and then there's us.

00:16:55.590 --> 00:17:01.862
So out of five
times, only once has

00:17:01.862 --> 00:17:04.819
any one of those branches
produced intelligent life.

00:17:04.819 --> 00:17:09.640
And the problem with
all of those branches

00:17:09.640 --> 00:17:14.859
is, if you follow
the family tree back,

00:17:14.859 --> 00:17:16.297
you get to one, single event.

00:17:16.297 --> 00:17:17.880
And this is the
really worrying thing.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:24.010
You follow all complex
multicellular life back,

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:27.599
you get to one event, which
was the creation of one

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:28.890
eukaryotic cell.

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:33.360
So basically, in the
most brief terms,

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:37.230
there were two types
of single-celled life

00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:40.150
on the Earth, the
bacteria and the archaea.

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:42.380
And then, again,
around something

00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:45.300
like a billion and a
half years ago, there

00:17:45.300 --> 00:17:50.830
was this one, single event
where a bacteria attempted--

00:17:50.830 --> 00:17:53.330
or, an archaea attempted
to consume a bacteria.

00:17:53.330 --> 00:17:58.060
And the two set up a kind
of hostage situation.

00:17:58.060 --> 00:18:00.470
And the bacteria then
evolved into what

00:18:00.470 --> 00:18:01.620
we call the mitochondria.

00:18:01.620 --> 00:18:04.090
And that's where
we get the energy

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:12.010
supply to fund the huge
information overhead

00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:15.930
of complex intelligent life.

00:18:15.930 --> 00:18:18.250
The beautiful thread that
runs through all of this

00:18:18.250 --> 00:18:20.860
is energy and information.

00:18:20.860 --> 00:18:27.790
So we need that constant source
of energy in the vent to power

00:18:27.790 --> 00:18:30.400
the creation of the
very first proto-life.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:37.960
And then we need-- and the great
innovation of what biologists

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:41.470
call eukaryotes, creatures like
ourselves which are made up

00:18:41.470 --> 00:18:45.160
of not these simple cells,
but these incredibly complex

00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:50.730
eukaryotic cells, the great
innovation there is we have

00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:54.380
basically enslaved
bacteria into our--

00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:58.900
Within each of our cells, there
are these mini power plants

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:01.270
producing this enormous
amount of energy

00:19:01.270 --> 00:19:05.330
so that we can store all that
information in a cell nucleus.

00:19:07.870 --> 00:19:10.170
And we can suddenly
start to have

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:12.912
really, really complex life.

00:19:12.912 --> 00:19:14.870
And as far as we know,
that only happened once.

00:19:14.870 --> 00:19:15.920
MALE SPEAKER: And that's
the bottleneck, really.

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:17.750
BEN MILLER: That's a bottleneck
that we've got to get through.

00:19:17.750 --> 00:19:19.330
MALE SPEAKER: Microbial
life-- quite common.

00:19:19.330 --> 00:19:20.246
That's the bottleneck.

00:19:20.246 --> 00:19:21.630
And then once you
get past that--

00:19:21.630 --> 00:19:24.150
BEN MILLER: Shocking bottleneck.

00:19:24.150 --> 00:19:27.900
Now there is one
element of hope,

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:31.200
which is, this did happen,
arguably, one other time, which

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:32.340
is in plants.

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:37.280
So what happened was the
archaea enslaved a bacterium,

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:39.790
created a eukaryotic
cell, and basically

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:44.670
created mitochondria, the
powerhouse of eukaryotic cells.

00:19:44.670 --> 00:19:49.510
Then, another amazing
thing happened.

00:19:49.510 --> 00:19:52.550
The other great innovation,
arguably, in evolution,

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:56.390
is photosynthesis.

00:19:56.390 --> 00:19:59.830
Unlike in the vent, where
metals where the food,

00:19:59.830 --> 00:20:02.950
it's taking light energy
and using that to power

00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:05.540
the stripping of electrons
from water and pushing that.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:08.900
So it's only light, which
is an incredibly good supply

00:20:08.900 --> 00:20:11.090
of water, which is an
incredibly good supply, both

00:20:11.090 --> 00:20:13.150
used to produce long-chain
carbon molecules.

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:16.740
That's a hugely
important innovation.

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:21.140
And that happened when a
eukaryotic cell enslaved

00:20:21.140 --> 00:20:23.670
what's called a cyanobacteria.

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:25.370
Basically, it was
a type of bacterium

00:20:25.370 --> 00:20:28.370
that had evolved chlorophyll.

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:29.830
And that's what created plants.

00:20:29.830 --> 00:20:33.670
So there's a chink of
hope there in that that's

00:20:33.670 --> 00:20:35.200
the same process, basically.

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:40.170
That's one cell
enslaving another cell

00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:42.630
to do its dirty business.

00:20:42.630 --> 00:20:48.280
So we enslaved the mitochondria.

00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:52.110
We also enslaved the
plasma into our own plants.

00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:53.440
So there's some hope.

00:20:53.440 --> 00:20:56.180
You could maybe argue,
well, it happened twice

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:57.840
in the history of life on Earth.

00:20:57.840 --> 00:21:00.122
But you can't get
away from the fact

00:21:00.122 --> 00:21:02.205
that the plant thing
happened after the eukaryote,

00:21:02.205 --> 00:21:04.140
so you've still got the
bottleneck back there.

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:06.247
You've still got the
eukaryotic bottleneck.

00:21:06.247 --> 00:21:08.330
And that's the thing that
keeps me awake at night,

00:21:08.330 --> 00:21:10.732
frankly, I think.

00:21:10.732 --> 00:21:15.690
So I just think, this
isn't great, is it?

00:21:15.690 --> 00:21:18.040
We've only got one example
of life to work on,

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:22.015
but there's still a
lot of information

00:21:22.015 --> 00:21:23.640
there, in the history
of life on Earth.

00:21:23.640 --> 00:21:26.300
But we're thinking--
it just ends up

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:30.160
with me thinking that,
intelligent life-- not common--

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:32.342
not nonexistent, but not common.

00:21:32.342 --> 00:21:34.800
MALE SPEAKER: So if we assume
that intelligence life is out

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:36.380
there-- let's skip to the
other end of the book--

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:37.290
you talk about messaging--

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:37.800
BEN MILLER: Yeah, messaging.

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:39.480
MALE SPEAKER: --so, if we
were to receive a message,

00:21:39.480 --> 00:21:40.563
what that might look like.

00:21:40.563 --> 00:21:42.850
And you used the example
of hieroglyphs as something

00:21:42.850 --> 00:21:45.470
that, we had a message, we
saw the information there,

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:46.805
but we couldn't
understand how to read it.

00:21:46.805 --> 00:21:48.388
BEN MILLER: This is
a fantastic story.

00:21:48.388 --> 00:21:51.670
This is a fabulous story,
particularly, I imagine,

00:21:51.670 --> 00:21:54.970
if your brain enjoys
coding and decoding.

00:21:54.970 --> 00:21:56.790
I mean, this is
just a great story.

00:21:56.790 --> 00:21:59.960
So it's the closest thing--
I was trying to think,

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:03.750
what is the closest that
we've ever got, as a species,

00:22:03.750 --> 00:22:07.620
to decoding the messages
of another species.

00:22:07.620 --> 00:22:09.240
And the best example
I could think of

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:14.760
was, in the 19th century,
when they were attempting

00:22:14.760 --> 00:22:18.380
to-- when Egypt was
suddenly opened up again,

00:22:18.380 --> 00:22:22.300
to the Western world,
through Napoleon's attempt

00:22:22.300 --> 00:22:28.062
to colonize it, and suddenly,
we had this flood of-- I mean,

00:22:28.062 --> 00:22:30.520
there had been a few Egyptian
monuments, obviously, in Rome

00:22:30.520 --> 00:22:32.811
that the Romans had collected
and brought back to Rome.

00:22:32.811 --> 00:22:37.020
But really, they were mainly
what they call cartouches,

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:38.867
basically, the throne
names of the kings.

00:22:38.867 --> 00:22:40.700
Those happened to be
the monuments they had.

00:22:40.700 --> 00:22:42.600
They didn't have a
great deal of text.

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:48.910
And when Napoleon attempted
to colonize Egypt,

00:22:48.910 --> 00:22:54.620
he took with him a shipload
of the French intelligentsia.

00:22:54.620 --> 00:22:56.120
This is just such
a brilliant story.

00:22:56.120 --> 00:22:58.190
They're called the savants.

00:22:58.190 --> 00:23:04.460
And among them were Fourier,
the French mathematician,

00:23:04.460 --> 00:23:06.804
there were some extraordinary
French biologists.

00:23:06.804 --> 00:23:07.470
They collected--

00:23:07.470 --> 00:23:08.900
MALE SPEAKER: Oh,
Fourier, as in tran--

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:09.870
BEN MILLER: Yeah,
as in transforms.

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:10.369
Yeah.

00:23:10.369 --> 00:23:11.290
Yeah.

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:17.080
And they collected an
enormous amount of text.

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:20.500
Suddenly, they discovered,
wow, it's not just these throne

00:23:20.500 --> 00:23:21.650
names on the monument.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:23.640
There is a language here.

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:27.710
And they just couldn't crack it.

00:23:27.710 --> 00:23:32.500
I mean, it took-- it's an
extraordinary story of how they

00:23:32.500 --> 00:23:36.810
eventually managed to-- a
French character, Champollion,

00:23:36.810 --> 00:23:41.210
finally managed to--
crack the hieroglyphs.

00:23:41.210 --> 00:23:43.050
You know Young's slits?

00:23:43.050 --> 00:23:46.246
You remember Young, the--

00:23:46.246 --> 00:23:47.370
MALE SPEAKER: Thomas Young.

00:23:47.370 --> 00:23:51.630
BEN MILLER: Thomas Young,
the British-- well,

00:23:51.630 --> 00:23:58.900
among many things-- physicist,
he got part of the way there,

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:02.860
because he managed to guess-- he
had-- actually, ironically, it

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:05.731
was the throne names that
enabled them to crack the code.

00:24:05.731 --> 00:24:08.230
MALE SPEAKER: Did they have the
Rosetta stone at that point?

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:09.310
BEN MILLER: Yeah, well,
the Rosetta stone--

00:24:09.310 --> 00:24:11.120
it was the discovery
that-- yes, absolutely.

00:24:11.120 --> 00:24:11.970
MALE SPEAKER: Maybe
explain what that

00:24:11.970 --> 00:24:13.630
is in case people don't know.

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:16.730
BEN MILLER: So basically,
it's all over there

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:17.885
for the French in Egypt.

00:24:17.885 --> 00:24:19.260
They're kind of
on their way out.

00:24:22.940 --> 00:24:25.040
They're trying to
build a fort at what

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:28.800
used to be called
Rosetta on the Nile.

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:31.980
And one of the soldiers
discovers-- basically,

00:24:31.980 --> 00:24:33.230
it's just a part of the wall.

00:24:33.230 --> 00:24:34.010
It's just one of the bricks.

00:24:34.010 --> 00:24:35.551
They're taking down
this ancient wall

00:24:35.551 --> 00:24:37.994
to rebuild it-- is a stone.

00:24:37.994 --> 00:24:40.160
And then, there are three
inscriptions on the stone.

00:24:43.870 --> 00:24:45.640
One, they recognize
straight away

00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:48.330
as the Egyptian hieroglyphs.

00:24:48.330 --> 00:24:50.290
And there are two
other types of--

00:24:50.290 --> 00:24:50.840
MALE SPEAKER: Greek and Coptic?

00:24:50.840 --> 00:24:51.673
BEN MILLER: --Greek.

00:24:51.673 --> 00:24:54.930
Yeah, there's Coptic, and then
there's another type of Greek.

00:24:54.930 --> 00:24:56.960
I believe it was Demotic.

00:24:56.960 --> 00:24:59.550
So they've got one kind of
Greek that they recognize,

00:24:59.550 --> 00:25:01.550
another kind of Greek
that they don't recognize,

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:02.478
and the hieroglyphs.

00:25:05.900 --> 00:25:09.120
And one of the savants
made the guess,

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:12.030
this could be the same bit of
text written in these three

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:12.530
languages.

00:25:12.530 --> 00:25:14.040
MALE SPEAKER: And it's
really boring text, isn't it?

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:15.170
BEN MILLER: It's so dull.

00:25:15.170 --> 00:25:16.720
Yeah, it's really dull.

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:21.420
It's basically a
kind of a eulogy.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:24.870
It's saying how
they should honor

00:25:24.870 --> 00:25:30.000
one of the kings of Egypt,
and it's really, really dull.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:34.300
I mean, it's really, really,
extraordinarily detailed--

00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:36.920
you know, this offering
must be made on this day.

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:41.270
And it's sort of like
bureaucracy, really,

00:25:41.270 --> 00:25:42.560
in the extreme.

00:25:42.560 --> 00:25:46.080
But this text was, of
course, what enabled

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:48.130
them to crack the hieroglyphs.

00:25:48.130 --> 00:25:50.280
And that's exactly
what we don't have when

00:25:50.280 --> 00:25:51.716
we receive our alien message.

00:25:54.460 --> 00:25:57.780
We have no idea of knowing
what is in the message.

00:25:57.780 --> 00:25:58.850
We can make guesses.

00:25:58.850 --> 00:26:01.609
We can hope that the
mathematics is universal.

00:26:01.609 --> 00:26:03.900
And they might send us prime
numbers to start off with.

00:26:03.900 --> 00:26:08.130
And maybe they'll send us
a few fundamental constants

