measuring system
you use, things like

00:26:12.790 --> 00:26:15.897
the ratio of the charge
on an election to--

00:26:15.897 --> 00:26:16.730
MALE SPEAKER: Or Pi.

00:26:16.730 --> 00:26:17.479
BEN MILLER: Or Pi.

00:26:22.040 --> 00:26:24.600
We can hope that we know
what's in the messages.

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:27.749
But if we couldn't crank
the ancient-- you know,

00:26:27.749 --> 00:26:29.540
if we find it so hard
to crack the messages

00:26:29.540 --> 00:26:31.290
of the ancient Egyptians,
it's really hard

00:26:31.290 --> 00:26:37.000
to see what hope there would be
apart from through information

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:37.500
theory.

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:39.958
So this is the wonderful thing,
coming back to the science.

00:26:39.958 --> 00:26:47.150
This guy, Zipf, spotted--
this was news to me.

00:26:47.150 --> 00:26:50.520
It might not be news
to many people here.

00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:57.930
But this brilliant
discovery by this American,

00:26:57.930 --> 00:27:01.140
George Kingsley
Zipf-- so he noticed

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:05.070
that if there's anything
that involves humans,

00:27:05.070 --> 00:27:08.010
you can see a certain
kind of pattern.

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:12.300
So say, for example,
if you look at--

00:27:12.300 --> 00:27:15.640
and things obey a sort
of logarithmic scale.

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:18.610
So say, for example, the
richest man in Britain

00:27:18.610 --> 00:27:22.870
will be 10 times richer than
the 10th richest man, who

00:27:22.870 --> 00:27:26.690
will be 100 times richer
than the 100th richest man.

00:27:26.690 --> 00:27:31.010
And you see this pattern not
only throughout the whole

00:27:31.010 --> 00:27:34.870
of human civilization, but you
also see it in human language

00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:35.690
as well.

00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:39.410
So if you take any text-- I
mean absolutely any text--

00:27:39.410 --> 00:27:42.230
and you start plotting the
frequency of occurrence

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:45.990
of words against
their rank, you get

00:27:45.990 --> 00:27:48.450
a straight logarithmic plot.

00:27:48.450 --> 00:27:53.990
So in other words, there are
features of human interaction

00:27:53.990 --> 00:27:58.047
and human language that are
independent of the messaging

00:27:58.047 --> 00:27:58.880
system that you use.

00:27:58.880 --> 00:27:59.770
MALE SPEAKER: It works
in all languages,

00:27:59.770 --> 00:28:01.440
and it seems to be
inbuilt to nature.

00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:02.690
BEN MILLER: Inbuilt to nature.

00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:04.900
And they did it with dolphins.

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:10.300
And they also found that dolphin
whistles obey this Zipf plot--

00:28:10.300 --> 00:28:12.680
not baby dolphins,
because they babble,

00:28:12.680 --> 00:28:15.860
not adolescent dolphins,
because they just slag off

00:28:15.860 --> 00:28:17.490
their parents the whole time.

00:28:17.490 --> 00:28:22.700
But adult dolphins, you get this
beautiful, straight Zipf plot

00:28:22.700 --> 00:28:26.220
if you plot their most
frequently used whistles

00:28:26.220 --> 00:28:28.920
against the rank
of that frequency.

00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:30.720
It's absolutely amazing.

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:33.800
And this comes back to
the work of Claude Shannon

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:39.880
and the fantastic work he
did in information theory

00:28:39.880 --> 00:28:42.910
in showing that the
potential information

00:28:42.910 --> 00:28:46.050
content of a message--
you can figure out

00:28:46.050 --> 00:28:48.837
what the potential information
content is without knowing

00:28:48.837 --> 00:28:49.670
what the message is.

00:28:49.670 --> 00:28:53.350
And this is our best
hope, basically,

00:28:53.350 --> 00:28:55.610
when we receive any messages.

00:28:55.610 --> 00:28:56.640
So what does it mean?

00:28:56.640 --> 00:28:58.927
It means when we're
messaging to aliens,

00:28:58.927 --> 00:29:00.676
you guys are going to
be really important,

00:29:00.676 --> 00:29:04.040
because we're going to have
to send the whole internet.

00:29:04.040 --> 00:29:06.980
We'll send the
whole thing, photos

00:29:06.980 --> 00:29:15.474
included, for several reasons.

00:29:15.474 --> 00:29:17.640
I think it's important, in
this exercise, that we're

00:29:17.640 --> 00:29:19.880
honest about who we
are, that we think

00:29:19.880 --> 00:29:25.680
about our responsibilities
as a species,

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:28.390
that we take our global
organizations seriously,

00:29:28.390 --> 00:29:36.700
that we consider
what we have to say

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:39.350
to other intelligent
alien species

00:29:39.350 --> 00:29:41.440
out there, what
we have to offer,

00:29:41.440 --> 00:29:43.020
what we're hoping to receive.

00:29:43.020 --> 00:29:44.760
And we just send
them everything,

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:48.540
because the chances of them
being able to decode it

00:29:48.540 --> 00:29:52.620
are minimal unless they have
a vast, vast amount of data,

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:55.490
and vice versa.

00:29:55.490 --> 00:29:57.950
We don't want to just get
a picture of a stick man--

00:29:57.950 --> 00:29:59.600
you know, the stuff that
we've been sending out.

00:29:59.600 --> 00:30:01.395
MALE SPEAKER: On Voyager 1, it's
just a stick man and some DNA.

00:30:01.395 --> 00:30:03.520
BEN MILLER: Yeah, on Voyager
1, a little stick man,

00:30:03.520 --> 00:30:06.520
a naked woman, and a
walking stick or whatever.

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:07.940
We just send a lot.

00:30:07.940 --> 00:30:09.899
We just send the
internet, the whole thing.

00:30:09.899 --> 00:30:11.940
MALE SPEAKER: Let's see
if there's any questions.

00:30:11.940 --> 00:30:14.000
So the book covers
quite a wide range.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:14.794
Yeah.

00:30:14.794 --> 00:30:17.698
AUDIENCE: So all the
things that keep you up

00:30:17.698 --> 00:30:19.150
at night, [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:28.490 --> 00:30:31.030
If humanity survives, we'll
eventually fill the galaxy.

00:30:31.030 --> 00:30:33.040
Our descendants, or the
nearest equivalents,

00:30:33.040 --> 00:30:35.530
will fill the galaxy
and the galaxies nearby.

00:30:35.530 --> 00:30:37.760
And no alien species
has done that yet.

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:38.980
So we're not seeing them.

00:30:38.980 --> 00:30:41.900
Something is between
them and doing that.

00:30:41.900 --> 00:30:46.340
And either that something is
behind us or it is ahead of us.

00:30:46.340 --> 00:30:49.610
If the problem is that
complex multicellular

00:30:49.610 --> 00:30:51.870
life, eukaryotic
cells and stuff,

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:55.260
are very, very
rare in the galaxy,

00:30:55.260 --> 00:30:56.520
that means it's behind us.

00:30:56.520 --> 00:30:59.150
That means that we can
rest easy that we're

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:01.800
going to make to the
rest of the galaxy.

00:31:01.800 --> 00:31:04.370
If it's ahead of us, we
should be very pessimistic.

00:31:04.370 --> 00:31:05.880
And I worry about that.

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:08.432
So every time I hear
something that says,

00:31:08.432 --> 00:31:10.890
this is why alien life is rare,
it's because of some filter

00:31:10.890 --> 00:31:14.579
that we've gone through,
then I feel better.

00:31:14.579 --> 00:31:15.620
BEN MILLER: Yeah, me too.

00:31:15.620 --> 00:31:18.059
And of course, there's another
possibility, isn't there,

00:31:18.059 --> 00:31:20.350
which is, it's there, but
it's simply not visible to us

00:31:20.350 --> 00:31:23.670
because we just simply aren't
looking for the right thing.

00:31:23.670 --> 00:31:27.890
And if we think how transient
our technologies are--

00:31:27.890 --> 00:31:35.120
we send our first signals-- our
first narrowband signals were

00:31:35.120 --> 00:31:37.530
radio waves that were just
blasted out everywhere

00:31:37.530 --> 00:31:38.180
into space.

00:31:41.300 --> 00:31:43.690
We then went almost
radio silent as we

00:31:43.690 --> 00:31:47.510
started to-- our
own communications

00:31:47.510 --> 00:31:51.640
became via satellites and cable.

00:31:51.640 --> 00:31:55.610
We're now starting to use--
laser communication is probably

00:31:55.610 --> 00:31:58.780
a much more energy
efficient and reliable

00:31:58.780 --> 00:32:03.580
way to set up some kind
of interstellar network.

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:06.010
So that's probably the
way we're going next.

00:32:06.010 --> 00:32:07.010
How long will that last?

00:32:07.010 --> 00:32:11.270
Maybe that lasts 10, 20
years before we're modulating

00:32:11.270 --> 00:32:12.760
neutron beams or something.

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:13.273
Who knows?

00:32:18.700 --> 00:32:20.930
I take some comfort from that.

00:32:20.930 --> 00:32:27.700
I think, well, we are
passing our-- so transient,

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:30.540
these technologies
and what we use.

00:32:30.540 --> 00:32:33.020
Already, the
classical information

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:35.270
that we've got on
the internet, there's

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:38.330
going to be a new
phase where we surely

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:42.360
will move into some other kind
of more quantum-based-- we'll

00:32:42.360 --> 00:32:46.970
move into some other kind of
way of moving of computing

00:32:46.970 --> 00:32:48.220
if not of storing information.

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:54.760
So maybe they're there,
it's just like they've just

00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:56.090
kicked over an ant hill.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:59.537
And we mean nothing to them,
and they mean nothing to us.

00:32:59.537 --> 00:33:00.536
Do you know what I mean?

00:33:00.536 --> 00:33:01.860
MALE SPEAKER: In fact, you used
the example, at the beginning,

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:05.060
where if a species out that
discovers Voyager 1 floating

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:07.810
through the galaxy, if they're
superintelligent bacteria,

00:33:07.810 --> 00:33:08.740
it's a snack.

00:33:08.740 --> 00:33:11.156
But if they're
huge and ginormous,

00:33:11.156 --> 00:33:12.780
they'll miss it,
because it's so small.

00:33:12.780 --> 00:33:16.540
So we assume people
are like us-- people.

00:33:16.540 --> 00:33:19.660
BEN MILLER: Yeah, we make--
and with some justification.

00:33:19.660 --> 00:33:22.970
Because any life that's
on a terrestrial planet,

00:33:22.970 --> 00:33:25.870
we can reasonably assume
that the same tropes

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:28.350
of intelligence,
sociability, languagee--

00:33:28.350 --> 00:33:31.190
we can reasonably assume that
those will crop up again.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:33.090
They won't necessarily
look anything like us.

00:33:33.090 --> 00:33:34.923
Their biology might be
completely different.

00:33:34.923 --> 00:33:38.280
They might be more closely
related to octopuses

00:33:38.280 --> 00:33:39.735
than they are to shrews.

00:33:42.261 --> 00:33:44.635
MALE SPEAKER: But they are
likely to have limbs, weapons,

00:33:44.635 --> 00:33:46.770
eyes, features that we
see over and over again.

00:33:46.770 --> 00:33:46.810
BEN MILLER: Exactly.

00:33:46.810 --> 00:33:48.935
Yeah, and they'll have had
a similar journey to us.

00:33:48.935 --> 00:33:51.080
But then, there's all
kinds of other things

00:33:51.080 --> 00:33:53.410
that could possibly
be out there.

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:02.290
It's a fascinating
problem to grapple with,

00:34:02.290 --> 00:34:04.510
because the only way you
can look for anything else

00:34:04.510 --> 00:34:06.970
is by assuming it's like you.

00:34:06.970 --> 00:34:08.810
Do you know what I mean?

00:34:08.810 --> 00:34:12.915
But you're automatically,
then, just completely reducing

00:34:12.915 --> 00:34:14.540
your opportunities
of finding anything.

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:19.710
So there's a real dilemma
right at the heart of it.

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:20.710
MALE SPEAKER: Questions.

00:34:23.839 --> 00:34:24.380
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:34:24.380 --> 00:34:28.120
Have you thought a little bit
about whether it's wise for us

00:34:28.120 --> 00:34:29.620
to be sending out signals?

00:34:29.620 --> 00:34:31.150
What do you think
the expected value

00:34:31.150 --> 00:34:33.830
is that our first
encounter will be positive

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:36.019
for humanity as opposed
to possibly catastrophic?

00:34:36.019 --> 00:34:38.310
MALE SPEAKER: Because Stephen
Hawking is very negative,

00:34:38.310 --> 00:34:39.110
isn't he?

00:34:39.110 --> 00:34:46.030
BEN MILLER: Yeah, I'm not
so-- don't get me wrong,

00:34:46.030 --> 00:34:49.739
some days, I think, oh
god, what are we doing.

00:34:49.739 --> 00:34:53.000
But then I think, well, we have
been broadcasting-- it's a bit

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:53.750
late now.

00:34:53.750 --> 00:35:00.010
We've been broadcasting for
about 100 years, haven't we?

00:35:00.010 --> 00:35:01.700
Was it the 1930s?

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:05.840
I suppose, a good 70, 80
years, we've been going.

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:10.800
So we're already 70 light-years
out in terms of stuff

00:35:10.800 --> 00:35:13.440
that knows we're here.

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:21.587
So how is this going to pan out?

00:35:21.587 --> 00:35:24.170
I certainly would expect that,
within 70 light-years of Earth,

00:35:24.170 --> 00:35:29.060
there would be other
microbial life.

00:35:29.060 --> 00:35:31.240
Do any of us necessarily
think that there

00:35:31.240 --> 00:35:32.940
would be intelligent life?

00:35:32.940 --> 00:35:36.400
That seems unlikely.

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:41.476
Intelligent life at some time
within the last 14.7 billion

00:35:41.476 --> 00:35:41.975
years?

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:46.780
Interestingly, there's
a kind of cutoff.

00:35:46.780 --> 00:35:49.710
As we look back in the galaxy,
we look further back in time,

00:35:49.710 --> 00:35:52.630
it seems less likely that
life could have survived.

00:35:52.630 --> 00:35:55.810
You go back more than about 5
billion years and galaxies are

00:35:55.810 --> 00:36:04.760
so active, so
energetic-- there's

00:36:04.760 --> 00:36:08.410
so much really hard
electromagnetic radiation

00:36:08.410 --> 00:36:11.280
around-- it's hard to
see how life could exist.

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:13.522
So you're looking at
a window of about--

00:36:13.522 --> 00:36:14.730
this is an interesting thing.

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:18.230
We're looking at a light
sphere of about 5 billion years

00:36:18.230 --> 00:36:20.530
around us where there
could conceivably

00:36:20.530 --> 00:36:24.410
be intelligent life.

00:36:24.410 --> 00:36:28.830
And interestingly, our planet
is around about that age.

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:30.670
I find that interesting too.

00:36:30.670 --> 00:36:33.380
There couldn't really
be life much older

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:35.864
than about 5 billion years.

00:36:35.864 --> 00:36:37.280
Still, you've got
to figure, there

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:39.860
could be life out there with a
half-billion-year start on us

00:36:39.860 --> 00:36:41.480
as of right now.

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:43.370
And of course,
communication, once you

00:36:43.370 --> 00:36:45.940
start to get out further and
further into the universe,

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:47.740
it's that travel time.

00:36:47.740 --> 00:36:49.730
So I just think it's
so far away that it

00:36:49.730 --> 00:36:51.920
will be a great experience.

00:36:51.920 --> 00:36:56.350
If we pick something up,
we'll know it's a signal.

00:36:56.350 --> 00:37:00.790
We won't necessarily know,
for a long time, what's in it.

00:37:00.790 --> 00:37:05.590
There's no way, unless
Stephen Hawking's right,

00:37:05.590 --> 00:37:08.370
and they can wormhole here
and hoover up all our water

00:37:08.370 --> 00:37:12.870
and then bugger
off somewhere else.

00:37:12.870 --> 00:37:14.750
I mean, maybe.

00:37:14.750 --> 00:37:15.370
Maybe.

00:37:15.370 --> 00:37:17.080
But it seems to me
that they're not here

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:19.690
because it's a really,
really big place

00:37:19.690 --> 00:37:22.030
and there's a
fundamental timing issue.

00:37:22.030 --> 00:37:24.500
Civilizations,
maybe, don't last.

00:37:24.500 --> 00:37:26.590
And certainly, technologies,
if not civilizations,

00:37:26.590 --> 00:37:29.770
don't last long enough
for civilizations

00:37:29.770 --> 00:37:35.540
to be visible to one another
at exactly the right moment.

00:37:35.540 --> 00:37:36.760
Anyway.

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:38.670
MALE SPEAKER: Yes, sir.

00:37:38.670 --> 00:37:40.740
Use the mic.

00:37:40.740 --> 00:37:43.890
AUDIENCE: You talked a
lot about biological life.

00:37:43.890 --> 00:37:47.080
And one of the
conclusions that I come to

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:53.640
is, if I wanted to travel
to another solar system,

00:37:53.640 --> 00:37:57.190
for example, I wouldn't
send a biological being.

00:37:57.190 --> 00:38:01.190
I would send an artificial
intelligence, or something,

00:38:01.190 --> 00:38:04.130
robot, because all the
scales fit so much better.

00:38:04.130 --> 00:38:06.250
And biology's quite messy.

00:38:06.250 --> 00:38:10.500
And we're not really adapted
for the space travel.

00:38:10.500 --> 00:38:13.350
Do you think if we
stopped talking about,

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:16.400
well, creatures with
arms and legs and eyes

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:20.005
and the idea of,
well, any sufficiently

00:38:20.005 --> 00:38:22.400
advanced civilization out
there would have actually gone

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:25.130
through the biological phase
and their progeny would actually

00:38:25.130 --> 00:38:28.110
be the machines they made-- they
may still exist in some form.

00:38:28.110 --> 00:38:30.710
But do you think
we're actually looking

00:38:30.710 --> 00:38:34.204
in the wrong places for
those kind of things as well?

00:38:34.204 --> 00:38:36.120
I guess that's sort of
an open-ended question.

00:38:36.120 --> 00:38:37.786
BEN MILLER: I completely
agree with you.

00:38:37.786 --> 00:38:42.110
Yeah, I think that it would
be-- we wouldn't expect--

00:38:42.110 --> 00:38:48.840
I mean, certainly, if alien
technology ever makes it here,

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:52.830
like you, I can't see how it
would possibly be biological.

00:38:52.830 --> 00:38:58.360
And we can see, from the way
that we're-- we don't even send

00:38:58.360 --> 00:38:59.900
people out into space anymore.

00:38:59.900 --> 00:39:02.004
We send robots.

00:39:02.004 --> 00:39:04.295
MALE SPEAKER: The head of
SETI thinks that-- because we

00:39:04.295 --> 00:39:05.336
were watching that video.

00:39:05.336 --> 00:39:06.330
I forgot his name.

00:39:06.330 --> 00:39:08.079
BEN MILLER: Martin
Rees is very, very good

00:39:08.079 --> 00:39:11.750
on this-- the Astronomer Royal,
Martin Reiss-- very, very

00:39:11.750 --> 00:39:13.940
good on the robots thing.

00:39:16.820 --> 00:39:20.420
That makes so much
sense, doesn't it?

00:39:20.420 --> 00:39:22.625
Again, this is one of the
things about the book.

00:39:22.625 --> 00:39:24.250
We're constantly
looking for ourselves.

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:27.920
There's some deep, primal
need, isn't there, out there

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:30.970
to find ourselves,
our own image.

00:39:30.970 --> 00:39:33.350
But if we're really
seriously going

00:39:33.350 --> 00:39:36.430
to look for alien
artifacts, then yeah,

00:39:36.430 --> 00:39:40.190
I think we are genuinely
looking in the wrong place.

00:39:40.190 --> 00:39:43.260
I saw a brilliant
article by Paul Davies

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:44.720
saying we should
check the Lagrange

00:39:44.720 --> 00:39:46.844
points around the Earth.

00:39:46.844 --> 00:39:47.760
We should have a look.

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:50.485
Is there anything there?

00:39:50.485 --> 00:39:52.610
We're sending stuff out.

